(622, 1, '2014-10-08 11:15:54', '2014-10-08 11:15:54', 'In June 2012 I was awarded for my Photoshop skills.\r\n\r\nHaving previously worked for Reliance, who had a contract with Sussex Police to create and organise the showing of Identification Parades to witnesses / victims of crimes, I was presented with a case involving the only image of the suspect available being a very old black and white passport photo that was rather worn and tattered. I had to match the appearance of this suspect with eight other males, similar in general appearance. I am not allowed to tamper with the original photograph.\r\n\r\nUsing my photoshop skills I acquired some images and made them look old fashioned, added all kinds of features like new hairstyles, old spectacles, beards to match the suspect, but not to be like clones. It was tough project, taking around 2 weeks to complete.\r\n\r\nThe ID parade that I created was then used as evidence as the witness was able to pick out the suspect, yet both accused and defense solicitors approved the ID as "fair for the suspect"\r\n\r\nIt was nice to be recognised for my work, I was praised by the CPS (Crown Prosecution Service), the Police detectives involved the case and Reliance presented with me this award, along with some vouchers to spend at River Island :)\r\n\r\n[button style="btn-default btn-lg" icon="fa fa-file-pdf-o" align="left" type="link" target="true" title="View certificate" link="http://localhost/jpmwordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/reliance.pdf"]', 'The Police praise my Photoshop skills', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'the-police-praise-my-photoshop-skills', '', '', '2014-10-08 11:15:54', '2014-10-08 11:15:54', '', 0, 'http://localhost/jpmwordpress//?p=622', 0, 'post', '', 0),
